<br>
Contingent Fees: One way people have mentioned to filter frivolous lawsuits is to ban contingent fees. These are fees where the lawyer takes a percentage of any settlement or jury award. Typically such an award will be around 25%, moving up to 30%-40% if the case is appealed. Some states limit what a lawyer can take explicitly, others implicitly through legal ethics codes promulgated by the bar. <br>
<br>
The problem with contingent fees is that they motivate both the unethical client to use the legal system as a sort of blackmail against defendants with deep pockets. There are lawyers who make quite a good living doing just that, and so its not hard to find representation. <br>
<br>
On the other hand, there are legitimate claims which would never see the light of day if not for contingent fees. Contingent fees originated in response to industrial injury cases before the advent of worker's compensation statutes. Back then, a worker who was injured was out on his keister with no money, but perhaps a legitimate claim for negligence against his employer. The cases were not easy to win, because of the prevalence of the fellow-servant rule at the time, which prevented many people from suing their employer for injuries caused by their fellow employees. So people with no resources could rarely find a lawyer willing to donate that much of his time for no return. Contingent fees allowed the very poor to bring legitimate claims against the very powerful, and quite often prevail.<br>
<br>
So how you feel about contingent fees depends on how many legitimate cases you are prepared to sacrifice to lose the frivolous cases. <br>
<br>
The same can be said of Tort-reform legislation. This is the second major movement, and attacks awards rather than the bringing of the case itself. The theory is that by limiting their claims to actual damages with a strict cap for things like emotional damages and loss of consortium, you reduce the incentive to file frivolous claims. Often frivolous claims have few provable medical damages, and inflated values for emotional distress etc. <br>
<br>
Again, the problem here is that those elements can serve legitimate purposes as well. Large verdicts attract public attention, and actually have an impact on large corporations in terms of increasing the marginal utility of creating safe and effective products. If these companies can settle out a lot of very small injury claims quickly, their incentive to do extensive testing of the safety of new products is reduced. <br>
<br>
So the question becomes, where do you set that cap so that unfair liability is controlled, yet you don't decrease the deterrance goal of the justice system. <br>
<br>
People dislike activist judges, but I for one would rather see that decided on a case by case basis in the courts than by the legislature. <br>
<br>
The big question is that where the factors in the system that promote frivolous lawsuits also serve legitimate justice purposes, where do you draw the lines? How many legitimate claims for justice are you willing to sacrifice for efficiency? How much is the slight to justice of unfair and frivolous cases worth compared to the cases that wont be brought? <br>
<br>
These are questions with no really good answers that courts struggle with regularly. My suggestion is that no significant changes are needed. The number of truly frivolous cases are small compared to the number of legitimate ones. I think the best way to handle them is twofold: First, state Bar Associations should step up their enforcement of the ethics codes and sanction those lawyers who are notorious for bringing and prosecuting these cases. Second, Judges should make more use of Federal Rule of Civil Procedure 11, and its state law counterparts, which allow them to sanction lawyers for the bringing of frivolous suits. The standards for what constitutes a frivolous and harassing suit should be tightened, and allow judges to use their good discretion in eliminating them from the docket.  <p>ICQ#-105127301<BR>
